sentences: Edgar Stillman Kelley (April 14, 1857 – November 12, 1944) was an American composer, conductor, teacher, and writer on music.
Kelley was of New England stock, his ancestors having come to America from England before 1650.
He was a talented artist and writer, but he decided to devote his life to music after a performance of Felix Mendelssohn's music for A Midsummer Night's Dream.
Two years later he went to Stuttgart, where he studied organ, piano, and composition.
Kelley graduated from the conservatory in Stuttgart in 1880, and performed around Europe for a time with a number of orchestras.

An interest in theater drew him to New York City in 1886, and there he married Jessie Gregg on July 23, 1891; the two then returned to California for four more years, during which time Kelley composed, conducted, lectured, and taught.

Kelley died in Oxford in 1944, and was buried in the Oxford Cemetery.

This music was to go on to become his most popular work; it is said to have been performed some five thousand times in English-speaking countries by 1930.
